{{Infobox ethnic group |group=Marabou |image=Marabou.jpg |caption=Marabou Haitian man |population=10,000+ |popplace=[[Haiti]], [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[France]]<ref>http://www.haiti.org</ref> | title= |rels=Predominantly [[Roman Catholic]], but also [[Anglican]], [[Protestant]], [[Baptist]], [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]], and [[Jehovah's Witness]]. |langs=[[French language|French]], [[Haitian Creole]], [[French-based creole languages]] |related=[[Afro-Caribbeans]], [[Dougla]], [[Indo-Caribbean]], [[Affranchi]] }} '''Marabou''' ({{lang-fr|marabout}}) is a term of [[Haiti]]an origin denoting multiracial admixture. The term describes the offspring of a Haitian person of mixed race: Africans, [[Ethnic groups in Europe|Europeans]], Taíno Indian and [[South Asian ethnic groups|South Asians]] ([[East Indians]]) ancestry.
The Marabou label dates to the colonial period of Haiti’s history, meaning the offspring of a mullato and a griffe person.<ref>{{cite book|author1=John Stephen Farmer|title=Americanisms--old & New|date=1889|page=377|quote=Mulatto. — A name given to the offspring of a white and a negro. The word is Spanish, mulato from mulo a mule, or, as in ... meamelouc ; Griffe, {{!}} black, negro and mulatto; Marabou, § black, mulatto and griffe; Sacatra, g black, griffe and negro.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Enciclopedia universal ilustrada europeo-americana|date=1925|publisher=[[Enciclopedia universal ilustrada europeo-americana]]|page=533|language=Spanish|quote=De este modo, el hijo de mulato y negra es un griffe, y el de griffe y negro unmarabou ó marabout y así sucesivamente.}}</ref> However, Médéric-Louis-Elie Moreau de Saint-Méry, in his 3-volume work on the colony<ref>Médéric-Louis-Elie Moreau de Saint-Méry. Description topographique, physique, civile, politique et historique de la partie francaise de lisle Saint-Domingue. 3 vols.(Philadelphia, 1797).</ref> describes Marabous as the product of the union of a black and a [[quadroon]], he says nothing concerning East Indians. The East Indian association with that term is probably due solely to the resemblance between dark-skinned Indians and marabous. Describing Marabous as an ethnic group is a stretch since the term applies to any person of mixed heritage with dark skin and straight or wavy hair. Marabous are no more an ethnic group than grimeaus, [[mulatto]]es, quadroons, or [[octoroon]]s are; these terms merely describe the different phenotypes of mixed-race people.
